        created by Francesco Cirillo in the late 1980s. The core idea behind
        the <strong>Pomodoro method</strong> is simple: work in focused
        intervals - traditionally 25 minutes - followed by a short break.
        After four focus sessions you take a longer break. Each interval is
        called a "pomodoro," named after the tomato-shaped kitchen timer
        Cirillo used as a student. This rhythm trains your brain to enter
        deep focus quickly while protecting you from burnout, making the
        <strong>Pomodoro study method</strong> one of the most popular focus systems
        in the world.
      </p>

